hands_on_practices.solution:
The Zaremba–Jaumann objective stress rate, denoted here by $\overset{\circ}{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$, provides a frame-indifferent measure of the rate of change of the Cauchy stress tensor $\boldsymbol{\sigma}$. Its definition is given by:
$$ \overset{\circ}{\boldsymbol{\sigma}} = \dot{\boldsymbol{\sigma}} - \boldsymbol{W} \boldsymbol{\sigma} + \boldsymbol{\sigma} \boldsymbol{W} $$
where $\dot{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$ is the material time derivative of the Cauchy stress tensor, and $\boldsymbol{W}$ is the spin tensor, which is the skew-symmetric part of the velocity gradient tensor $\boldsymbol{L}$.

First, we must determine the velocity gradient tensor $\boldsymbol{L}$ from the given velocity field $\mathbf{v} = (\dot{\gamma}y, 0)$. In the two-dimensional Cartesian coordinate system $(x, y)$, the components of $\mathbf{v}$ are $v_x = \dot{\gamma}y$ and $v_y = 0$. The components of the velocity gradient tensor, $L_{ij} = \frac{\partial v_i}{\partial x_j}$, are computed as:
$$
\boldsymbol{L} = \nabla\mathbf{v} =
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{\partial v_x}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial v_x}{\partial y} \\
\frac{\partial v_y}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial v_y}{\partial y}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\frac{\partial (\dot{\gamma}y)}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial (\dot{\gamma}y)}{\partial y} \\
\frac{\partial (0)}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial (0)}{\partial y}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & \dot{\gamma} \\
0 & 0
\end{pmatrix}
$$
The spin tensor $\boldsymbol{W}$ is defined as $\boldsymbol{W} = \frac{1}{2}(\boldsymbol{L} - \boldsymbol{L}^T)$. The transpose of $\boldsymbol{L}$ is:
$$
\boldsymbol{L}^T =
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & 0 \\
\dot{\gamma} & 0
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Thus, the spin tensor is:
$$
\boldsymbol{W} = \frac{1}{2} \left(
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & \dot{\gamma} \\
0 & 0
\end{pmatrix}
-
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & 0 \\
\dot{\gamma} & 0
\end{pmatrix}
\right) = \frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & \dot{\gamma} \\
-\dot{\gamma} & 0
\end{pmatrix}
$$
The Cauchy stress tensor $\boldsymbol{\sigma}$ is symmetric, so in the $x$–$y$ plane it has the form:
$$
\boldsymbol{\sigma} =
\begin{pmatrix}
\sigma_{xx} & \sigma_{xy} \\
\sigma_{yx} & \sigma_{yy}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\sigma_{xx} & \sigma_{xy} \\
\sigma_{xy} & \sigma_{yy}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
The material derivative of the stress tensor $\dot{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$ is given by:
$$
\dot{\boldsymbol{\sigma}} =
\begin{pmatrix}
\dot{\sigma}_{xx} & \dot{\sigma}_{xy} \\
\dot{\sigma}_{xy} & \dot{\sigma}_{yy}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Now we compute the terms $\boldsymbol{W}\boldsymbol{\sigma}$ and $\boldsymbol{\sigma}\boldsymbol{W}$:
$$
\boldsymbol{W}\boldsymbol{\sigma} = \frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & \dot{\gamma} \\
-\dot{\gamma} & 0
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
\sigma_{xx} & \sigma_{xy} \\
\sigma_{xy} & \sigma_{yy}
\end{pmatrix}
= \frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix}
\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy} & \dot{\gamma} \sigma_{yy} \\
-\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xx} & -\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
$$
\boldsymbol{\sigma}\boldsymbol{W} = \frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix}
\sigma_{xx} & \sigma_{xy} \\
\sigma_{xy} & \sigma_{yy}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
0 & \dot{\gamma} \\
-\dot{\gamma} & 0
\end{pmatrix}
= \frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix}
-\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy} & \dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xx} \\
-\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{yy} & \dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Substituting these expressions into the definition of the Jaumann rate:
$$
\overset{\circ}{\boldsymbol{\sigma}} = \dot{\boldsymbol{\sigma}} - (\boldsymbol{W}\boldsymbol{\sigma} - \boldsymbol{\sigma}\boldsymbol{W})
$$
The correction term is:
$$
\boldsymbol{W}\boldsymbol{\sigma} - \boldsymbol{\sigma}\boldsymbol{W} = \frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix}
2\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy} & \dot{\gamma} (\sigma_{yy} - \sigma_{xx}) \\
\dot{\gamma} (\sigma_{yy} - \sigma_{xx}) & -2\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy} & \frac{\dot{\gamma}}{2} (\sigma_{yy} - \sigma_{xx}) \\
\frac{\dot{\gamma}}{2} (\sigma_{yy} - \sigma_{xx}) & -\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Therefore, the Zaremba–Jaumann rate is:
$$
\overset{\circ}{\boldsymbol{\sigma}} =
\begin{pmatrix}
\dot{\sigma}_{xx} & \dot{\sigma}_{xy} \\
\dot{\sigma}_{xy} & \dot{\sigma}_{yy}
\end{pmatrix}
-
\begin{pmatrix}
\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy} & \frac{\dot{\gamma}}{2} (\sigma_{yy} - \sigma_{xx}) \\
\frac{\dot{\gamma}}{2} (\sigma_{yy} - \sigma_{xx}) & -\dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
This simplifies to the final expression for the components of $\overset{\circ}{\boldsymbol{\sigma}}$:
$$
\overset{\circ}{\boldsymbol{\sigma}} =
\begin{pmatrix}
\dot{\sigma}_{xx} - \dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy} & \dot{\sigma}_{xy} + \frac{\dot{\gamma}}{2} (\sigma_{xx} - \sigma_{yy}) \\
\dot{\sigma}_{xy} + \frac{\dot{\gamma}}{2} (\sigma_{xx} - \sigma_{yy}) & \dot{\sigma}_{yy} + \dot{\gamma} \sigma_{xy}
\end{pmatrix}
$$
Upon inspection of this result, we identify the coupling between normal and shear stress components. The normal components of the objective rate, $\overset{\circ}{\sigma}_{xx}$ and $\overset{\circ}{\sigma}_{yy}$, explicitly depend on the shear stress component $\sigma_{xy}$. Conversely, the shear component of the objective rate, $\overset{\circ}{\sigma}_{xy}$, explicitly depends on the normal stress components $\sigma_{xx}$ and $\sigma_{yy}$. This coupling is a direct consequence of the rotational part of the deformation and is fundamental to the objective formulation of constitutive relations in rheology and solid mechanics. All components of the objective rate tensor exhibit this coupling.
